  "notes": "Ewe (Eʋegbe), Gbe (Atlantic-Congo), Ghana and Togo. Latin alphabet with the Africa Alphabet letters ɖ ƒ ɣ ŋ ɔ ɛ ʋ and the digraphs dz gb kp ny ts. Contrasts the bilabial fricatives ƒ /ɸ/ and ʋ /β/ with the labiodentals f /f/ and v /v/. Doubly-articulated stops gb /ɡ͡b/ and kp /k͡p/. Vowels a e ɛ i o ɔ u; nasalised vowels are written with a following ⟨n⟩ and are not separate graphemes. TONE: Ewe is a tonal language, but tone is written only where disambiguation requires it (acute, grave, caron, circumflex); the standard orthography is otherwise toneless, so no tone is emitted here and accented vowels are not listed.",
